4},[7135],{"#text":580},{"#text":872},{"#text":872},{"name":7139},[7140,7141,7144,7145,7148],{"#text":1545},{"surname":7142},[7143],{"#text":5079},{"#text":1545},{"given-names":7146},[7147],{"#text":5084},{"#text":872},{"#text":872},{"name":7151},[7152,7153,7156,7157,7160],{"#text":1545},{"surname":7154},[7155],{"#text":3797},{"#text":1545},{"given-names":7158},[7159],{"#text":3802},{"#text":872},{"#text":846},{"@_person-group-type":3877},{"#text":3884},{"article-title":7165},[7166],{"#text":7167},"Regulatory requirements for the quality of allergen products for allergen immunotherapy of food allergy",{"#text":3884},{"source":7170},[7171],{"#text":6567},{"#text":3890},{"year":7174},[7175],{"#text":2840},{"#text":3895},{"volume":7178},[7179],{"#text":1212},{"#text":3901},{"issue":7182},[7183],{"#text":1045},{"#text":3906},{"fpage":7186},[7187],{"#text":3380},{"#text":3884},{"pub-id":7190,":@":7193},[7191],{"#text":7192},"10.1007/s11882-021-01008-9",{"@_pub-id-type":3922},{"pub-id":7195,":@":7198},[7196],{"#text":7197},"33970347",{"@_pub-id-type":3928},{"@_citation-type":3930},{"#text":989},"40.",[7203,7204,7205],{"surname":7131,"givenNames":580},{"surname":5079,"givenNames":5084},{"surname":3797,"givenNames":3802},{"content":7207,"id":3510,"index":7232,"authors":7233,"title":19,"source":19,"volume":19,"year":19,"fpage":19,"lpage":19,"doi":19,"pmid":19},[7208,7209,7231],{"#text":3752},{"citation":7210,":@":7230},[7211,7212,7215,7216,7220,7221,7226,7229],{"#text":846},{"collab":7213},[7214],{"#text":6296},{"#text":3884},{"comment":7217},[7218],{"#text":7219},"Code of federal regulations: Part 211 - current good manufacturing practice for finished pharmaceuticals (2022). Available at",{"#text":3766},{"ext-link":7222,":@":7225},[7223],{"#text":7224},"https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-21/chapter-I/subchapter-C/part-211",{"@_ext-link-type":899,"@_xmlns:xlink":1323,"@_xlink:href":7224},{"comment":7227},[7228],{"#text":5663},{"#text":1492},{"@_citation-type":3778},{"#text":989},"41.",[],[7235],{"title":7236,"content":7237},"Contribution to the field Statement",[7238,7239,7242,7243,7252],{"#text":989},{"title":7240},[7241],{"#text":7236},{"#text":989},{"p":7244},[7245,7247,7250],{"#text":7246},"Use of peanut, a natural product, for oral immunotherapy (OIT) to manage peanut allergy is fraught with challenges including differences in potency and aflatoxin contamination. Peanut (",{"italic":7248},[7249],{"#text":787},{"#text":7251},") allergen powder-dnfp (PTAH; Palforzia®) is the first US Food and Drug Administration and first EU European Commission–approved OIT derived from peanut flour, for which the approvals require that manufacturing adheres to Good Manufacturing Practice and other regulatory requirements. Peanut sourcing/manufacturing processes, including standardization of allergens, ensure the resulting drug product is consistent. Testing drug substance for quality, safety, and potency ensures drug efficacy/safety is not affected by potency variability or contaminants. Between 2018 and 2021, 50% to 60% of peanut flour lots were rejected upon screening as unsuitable for drug substance testing. The most common reason for rejection was lots did not meet acceptance criteria for potencies of key immunodominant and clinically relevant allergens (Ara h 1, Ara h 2, and Ara h 6) considered responsible for peanut hypersensitivity. Other lots were unsuitable for safety or quality attributes. Because of stringent potency controls at all stages of manufacturing, severity of adverse events in PTAH clinical trials was unlikely due to allergen potency variations.",{"#text":992},[7254,7262,7274,7281,7288,7300,7536,7790,8021,8181],{"id":1299,"type":7255,"title":1309,"description":1317,"descriptionNodes":7256,"altText":19,"imageUrl":1324},"Figure",[7257,7258,7261],{"#text":846},{"p":7259},[7260],{"#text":1317},{"#text":852},{"id":1403,"type":7255,"title":1413,"description":7263,"descriptionNodes":7264,"altText":19,"imageUrl":1432},"PTAH source material selection process. Abbreviations: COA, Certificate of Analysis; ELISA, enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay; GPTN, Golden Peanut and Tree Nuts; HPLC, high-performance liquid chromatography; PTAH, peanut (Arachis hypogaea) allergen powder-dnfp.",[7265,7266,7273],{"#text":872},{"p":7267},[7268,7269,7272],{"#text":1421},{"italic":7270},[7271],{"#text":787},{"#text":1426},{"#text":846},{"id":2508,"type":7255,"title":2518,"description":2526,"descriptionNodes":7275,"altText":19,"imageUrl":2532},[7276,7277,7280],{"#text":872},{"p":7278},[7279],{"#text":2526},{"#text":846},{"id":1799,"type":7255,"title":2563,"description":2571,"descriptionNodes":7282,"altText":19,"imageUrl":2577},[7283,7284,7287],{"#text":872},{"p":7285},[7286],{"#text":2571},{"#text":846},{"id":2601,"type":7255,"title":2636,"description":7289,"descriptionNodes":7290,"altText":19,"imageUrl":2654},"Total aflatoxins in commercial peanut flour lots from 2010 to 2020. Peanut flour lots used in PTAH manufacturing are limited to no more than 4 ppb of total aflatoxins, shown by the red dashed line. GPTN would not manufacture peanut flour from peanut crop where the total aflatoxin exceeds 15 ppb. Abbreviations: GPTN, Golden Peanut and Tree Nuts; ppb, parts per billion; PTAH, peanut (Arachis hypogaea) allergen powder-dnfp.",[7291,7292,7299],{"#text":872},{"p":7293},[7294,7295,7298],{"#text":2644},{"italic":7296},[7297],{"#text":787},{"#text":1426},{"#text":846},{"id":1503,"type":7301,"title":1528,"description":1536,"descriptionNodes":7302,"tableNodes":7308,"tableFootNodes":7503,"imageUrl":19},"Table",[7303,7304,7307],{"#text":872},{"p":7305},[7306],{"#text":1536},{"#text":846},[7309],{"table":7310},[7311,7312,7323,7324,7341,7342,7502],{"#text":872},{"colgroup":7313},[7314,7315,7318,7319,7322],{"#text":1545},{"col":7316,":@":7317},[],{"@_align":1549},{"#text":1545},{"col":7320,":@":7321},[],{"@_align":1549},{"#text":872},{"#text":872},{"thead":7325},[7326,7327,7340],{"#text":1545},{"tr":7328},[7329,7330,7334,7335,7